    "summary": "Cleisthenes' Democratic Reforms (508/507 BC) were the constitutional changes that created Athenian democracy in its recognizable form — reorganizing the citizen body to break the power of aristocratic regional factions and create a truly mixed civic body. Cleisthenes replaced the old four Ionian tribes with ten new artificial tribes (phylai), each combining demes (local communities) from the three geographic zones of Attica (city, coast, inland) in equal proportions — a deliberate 'mixing up' of the old social networks that had sustained aristocratic clientage.\n\nThe reforms created a new Council of 500 (boule) with 50 representatives from each of the ten tribes chosen by lot — replacing Solon's Council of 400 and dramatically expanding direct citizen participation in governance. The tribal organization also structured the army (each tribe provided a regiment) and the games, creating shared civic identity across social and geographic divisions. Cleisthenes also introduced ostracism — the annual vote to exile any citizen deemed a threat to the democracy for ten years without loss of property — as a constitutional safety valve against tyranny. Herodotus attributed to Cleisthenes the 'isegoria' (equal right of speech) that he saw as the foundation of Athenian military success. His reforms of 508 BC are generally taken as the founding moment of democracy as a political system.",
